Recommendation
We recommended that:
Based on the assessment roll maintained by the Municipal Assessor, the Municipal Treasurer furnish the Municipal Accountant at the beginning of each year with a duly certified list showing the name of taxpayers and the amounts due and collectible for the year;
Based on the certified list provided by the Municipal Treasurer, the Municipal Accountant prepares a Journal Entry Voucher (JEV) to record as a debit the RPT Receivable/SET Receivable and as a credit the Deferred RPT/Deferred SET;
The Municipal Treasurer updates and completes its report or list of tax delinquencies as of a given period to facilitate the reconciliation of accounting and treasury records; and
Based on the updated and complete report or list of tax delinquencies, the Municipal Accountant conducts reconciliation and verification of the same, and effects the necessary adjustments in the LGU’s books of accounts to come up with the corrected balances of RPT Receivable/SET Receivable and Deferred RPT/Deferred SET.

Recommendation
We recommended that the:
Management take appropriate actions to demand the settlement of the undeposited cash collections of the former Municipal Treasurer;
Municipal Treasurer immediately settle/deposit all undeposited cash collections;
Henceforth, Municipal Treasurer to deposit intact all collections within the reglementary period, and implement necessary control measures for handling cash collections and deposits to prevent the accumulation of government funds in his possession which may expose them to the risk of loss, misuse, or misappropriation;
Municipal Accountant and Municipal Treasurer identify the discrepancies between the ledger and cashbook balances, and effect the necessary adjustments in their records to arrive at reconciled balances; and
Henceforth, Municipal Accountant and Municipal Treasurer conduct periodic reconciliation between the accounting’s ledgers and treasury’s cashbooks at least quarterly.
Management Comment
Management commented that the Municipal Treasurer has already deposited during CY 2025 some of the undeposited collections discussed above. Further, Management committed to comply with the audit recommendations.

Recommendation
We recommended that the Municipal Accountant:
Cause the immediate submission of all unsubmitted DVs and their supporting documents covering the calendar year 2024;
With the Municipal Treasurer, determine and resolve the causes of delay in the submission of DVs and their supporting documents and observe the timely submission of the same within reglementary period;
Ensure that all claims for disbursements are supported with complete documentation before the same are processed and forwarded to the Municipal Treasurer and the Municipal Mayor for their respective certifications and approval, and the preparation and issuance of checks or ADA;
Likewise, the Municipal Treasurer refrain from issuing checks or ADA in the absence or lack of DVs and supporting documents; and
With the Municipal Treasurer and the Local Chief Executive, ensure that all disbursements made through ADA are covered with DVs duly signed, certified and approved by them.
Management Comment
In his letter dated May 7, 2025, the Municipal Treasurer informed the audit team that out of the total unsubmitted DVs amounting to P42,607,796.17 as discussed above, 39 DVs amounting to P7,103,051.09 were already determined to be in their possession and subject for transmittal to the Municipal Accounting Office. In addition, four (4) checks amounting to P7,190.00 were already considered stale checks and had already been transmitted to the Municipal Accounting Office. Nevertheless, the Municipal Treasurer committed to submit the remaining DVs in their possession the soonest possible time.

Recommendation
We recommended, and Management agreed to:
Send demand letters to concerned accountable officers and employees, who are still in active service with the LGU, and to former officers and employees, and external debtors for the immediate liquidation and/or settlement of their unliquidated cash advances and/or other accountabilities, as applicable;
In case of non-settlement, Management may cause the withholding of salaries or any money claims due to officers and employees, who are still in active service with the LGU and/or file appropriate charges against them;
Through the Municipal Accountant, exert efforts to properly identify the accountable persons for those cash advances which were remarked as for reconciliation/refund in the schedule;
Strictly comply with the pertinent provisions of COA Circular No. 97-002 relative to the prescribed period for the liquidation of cash advances;
Refrain from granting additional cash advances to officers and employees who still have outstanding/unliquidated cash advances;
Through Municipal Accountant, issue a certification that previous cash advances have been fully liquidated and accounted for in the books as part of the documentary requirements prior to the granting of new cash advances; and
Initiate the request for the write-off of dormant unliquidated cash advances of accountable officers who are no longer connected with the LGU, following the guidelines, procedures, and documentary requirements pursuant to COA Circular No. 2016-005 dated December 19, 2016.

Recommendation
We recommended, and Management agreed to:
Review its existing Municipal Revenue Code and update some of its provisions including, but not limited to, the amounts of rental fees of all stalls/spaces in the public market and all commercial buildings owned by the LGU;
In coordination with the Sangguniang Bayan, pass and enact a new/updated Municipal Revenue Code and submit a copy of the same to the Office of the Auditor;
Execute and enter into lease contracts/agreements with existing lessees which were found to be without copies of lease contracts/agreements on file, and submit copies of the same to the Office of the Auditor;
Enter into a contract of lease indicating therein the rental fees and other conditions in the Municipal Revenue Code for any new lessee that may potentially occupy vacant spaces/stalls in the LGU’s Public Market and/or Commercial Buildings;
Strictly enforce the surcharge and other penalties for the late or non-payment of rental fees in accordance with the Municipal Revenue Code;
Exert earnest efforts to collect the unpaid balances from rental fees of concerned delinquent lessees. Otherwise, cause the removal or eviction of the concerned lessees from the leased stalls/spaces without prejudice to collection of their unpaid balances and the filing of appropriate charges, as applicable;
Through the Market In-Charge personnel, periodically submit to the Office of the Municipal Accountant the report on unpaid/delinquent rental fees, including the computation for applicable surcharges or penalties, for the proper recording by the latter of the appropriate receivable and income accounts in the financial statements; and
Through the Municipal Accountant, prepare the necessary adjustments to recognize the uncollected rental fees. Henceforth, properly account and record the appropriate receivables and earned income on stall/space rentals in the LGU’s books of accounts.
Management Comment
Management commented that the updated/revised Municipal Revenue Code has already been presented to the Sangguniang Bayan for deliberation and finalization. Further, Management expressed its commitment to comply with the audit recommendations.

Recommendation
We recommended, and Management agreed to:
Through the Municipal Budget Officer, conduct review and reconciliation of its SAAOB and RAAO for the 20 per cent Development Fund, and make the necessary adjustments for accurate reporting of the obligations incurred and unobligated balances as of year-end;
Moving forward, ensure that the identified development projects funded under the 20 per cent Development Fund are properly and timely implemented to achieve the desirable socio-economic targets and outcomes of the LGU;
Fast track the completion and/or implementation of development projects which remained ongoing and/or unimplemented as of year-end. Otherwise, consider the reprogramming of the same which may no longer be needed into other priority development projects;
Provide for the specific timeframe or timing of implementation for each development project rather than a uniform and generic timeframe such as January to December of a calendar year for all identified projects; and initiate the procurement procedures of these projects earlier during the calendar year rather than towards the middle or end of the year or avail of the procedures for the Early Procurement Activities (EPA) allowed under existing laws, rules and regulations to avoid delayed and/or non-implementation of projects;
Cautiously take into consideration the identified PPAs in the AIP and Annual Budget and refrain from incurring obligations for projects which are inconsistent with the projects identified in the AIP and funded in the Annual Budget; and
Submit to the Office of the Auditor all copies of MDC and SB resolutions approving the realignment of funds out of the 20 per cent Development Fund and the approved revised/supplemental AIP and supplemental budget.

Recommendation
We recommended, and Management agreed to open a separate depository bank account in the Trust Fund books to be used as depository of funds pertaining to the unexpended balances of the QRF and MF-MOOE which will be transferred to the STF.
We further recommended, and the Municipal Accountant agreed to:
Conduct cash analysis to determine the availability of cash to support the balances of the unexpended continuing appropriations for LDRRM Fund under the General Fund and unexpended STF under the Trust Fund;
In coordination with the Municipal Treasurer, cause the transfer of cash to the depository account maintained under the GF to come up with the equivalent amount of the unexpended balances of continuing appropriations for the LDRRM Fund;
After a separate depository bank account for the LDRRM Fund-STF in the Trust Fund has been opened, and in coordination with the Municipal Treasurer, cause the transfer of cash to the depository account for STF in the Trust Fund to come up with the equivalent amount of the unexpended balances of the LDRRM Fund-STF;
Review the balances of the Trust Liabilities – Disaster Risk Reduction and Management Fund account under the General Fund and prepare the necessary adjusting entries to reverse the entries made in previous years in order to come up with a zero balance for this account, taking into consideration that this account is used and maintained only for unexpended QRF and MF-MOOE, which were transferred into the STF in the Trust Fund books; and
Carefully review transactions and record only the unexpended balances of QRF and MF-MOOE that were transferred into the STF in the Trust Fund books as Transfers of Unspent Current Year DRRM Funds to the Trust Funds account. This account should exclude the unexpended balances of MF-CO which will remain in the books of the General Fund as continuing appropriations.

Recommendation
We recommended and the Municipal Accountant agreed to:
In coordination with the BAC and the Municipal Engineer, submit immediately the lacking supporting documents of disbursement vouchers pertaining to the subject infrastructure projects;
Require contractors the submission of an irrevocable standby letter of credit of equivalent value from a commercial bank, a bank guarantee or a surety bond callable upon demand to support their claim/request for advance payment for mobilization;
Require contractors the submission of warranty securities for completed and accepted infrastructure projects, in order to protect not only the interest of the government but also those project beneficiaries and other third parties involved in the execution of government projects;
Require the contractors the submission of any security in the form of cash, bank guaranty, irrevocable standby letter of credit from a commercial bank, GSIS or surety bond callable on demand to support their claim for the release of retention money; and
Carefully review, examine and ensure that disbursement vouchers for infrastructure projects are supported with complete and adequate supporting documents before such claims are processed and released for payment. Also, consider preparing a checklist of all documentary requirements related to the disbursements for infrastructure projects.
We further recommended, and the BAC, through its Secretariat, agreed to prepare and compile all pertinent documents relative to the conduct of procurement activities from the preparation of bidding documents, posting of invitations to bid up to the award of contract, and submit these documents to the Municipal Accountant as supporting documents to the disbursement vouchers for the payment of infrastructure projects, in addition to the advance copies of these documents together with the contract agreement for submission to the Office of the Auditor for the purpose of contract review.

